ted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRepresentation and Resistance: South Asian and African Women's Texts at Home and in the Diaspora compares colonial and national constructions of gender identity in Western-educated African and South Asian women's texts. Jaspal Kaur Singh argues that, while some writers conceptualize women's equality in terms of educational and professional opportunity, sexual liberation, and individualism, others recognize the limitations of a paradigm of liberation that focuses only on individual freedom. Certain diasporic artists and writers assert that transformation of gender identity construction occurs, but only in transnational cultural spaces of the first world-spaces which have emerged in an era of rampant globalization and market liberalism. In particular, Singh advocates the inclusion of texts from women of different classes, religions, and castes, both in the Global North and in the South.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican diaspora in literature. 0aAfrican literature (English)xWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aFeminism and literature. 0aPostcolonialism in literature. 0aSex role in literature. 0aSouth Asian diaspora in literature. 0aSouth Asian literature (English)xWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aSouth Asian literature (English). 0aSouth Asians. 0aWomen in literature. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781552382677?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781552382677423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781552382677/or